ok seeks to understand the moral and religious attitudes of groups within pluralistic societies whose traditions and beliefs raise for them unique questions about food and dietary practice. What questions are there for kosher Jews, halal Muslims, and vegetarian Hindus about food products containing transgenes from prohibited sources? How do these foods impact the cultural practices and spiritual teachings of indigenous peoples? Concerns from the above traditions as well as Christianity, Buddhism, Chinese religion, and ethical vegetarianism are included. Contributors look at the ethical context of each tradition and also include information from focus groups. This enlightening work concludes with recommendations for the labeling of genetically modified foods.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 4aEnvironmental Studies : Environmental Studies. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Comparative Religion. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Religion. 7aRELIGION / Religion & Science.2bisacsh1 aAbraham, Samuel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBruce, Donald, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrunk, Conrad G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrunk, Conrad G., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCoward, Harold, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCoward, Harold, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLoy, David R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLétourneau, Lyne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMazgul, Lorenzo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoosa, Ebrahim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNarayanan, Vasudha, econ